	</td>
	
	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_390349">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_390349"><font color="Navy"><center><font size="5">Guild Summit Report</font><br />
by<br />
<font size="3">Gemdiver Myrcide</font></center></font><br />
<br />
<br />
My impression of my three days in San Diego can be summed up by one word: astonishing. Lots of people know that recently I have been rather supportive of SoE despite the various bugs and issues with GoD  largely due to my high expectations for EQ2  but I could not have predicted the response we got.<br />
<br />
After picking up my bags at the airport I walked outside to wait for the bus. Seeing a group of three or four people  one of them was wearing a t-shirt which I saw as a good sign and headed on over (That person was Arminya from EQ Roleplayers).  From the start, we were talking about what was wrong with the game. There was a burned out guild leader, a disgruntled SK, myself, and Arminya  and from the start we were talking about things that could be changed to make EQ better. <br />
<br />
Thomas (Vannoth) greeted us at the bus and away we went to our hotel. After a little mingling in the bar we headed off to the Padres game which is where the real work started. At the game I spoke to a couple of the devs. I should say right now throughout my report Ill be mixing up names and using some EQ names and IRL names for other people because sometimes I mixed them up. <br />
<br />
I spoke to the spell guy (Travis I think?) a little bit, mainly about GoD familiars, draughts being too weak, lacking new lure spells, and of course pillars. I also spoke with the guy in charge of the Breakdown in Communication quest  everyone will be happy to know that (a) The pages for the Yxtta part are being changed so that 1 group can obtain them and (b) Night watchman Fxi is being looked at. <br />
<br />
I spent most of my time talking with an associate producer named Craig though. Throughout the course of the weekend he was most likely the person I spoke the most with and was very helpful. We spoke about a variety of things including revamping of old zones, PoK making the world smaller, AAs, and other general things like what SoE was trying to get out of the summit. He was really interested in the state of the server and was asked a lot of questions. That was the first thing that impressed me about everyone  questions. <br />
<br />
A lot of people thought the event might be a PR gig where people voiced their complaints and they fell on deaf ears  it couldnt be further from the truth. Craig and everyone was always asking about what was wrong, would this work, if not what could they do instead, do we think that players would want this, do we think doing that would trivialize other parts of the game  They wanted to know how we felt and constantly were taking notes.<br />
<br />
The game ended and we headed back to the hotel. I went up to my room to change and found a nice little SoE bag stocked with a new gaming keyboard, free omens of war CD key, and other goodies. Then I headed back to the bar to meet some of the various people and chat a little bit with Brenlo and Thomas. I should mention, and this isnt to kiss anyones ass, that Brenlo absolutely rocks. It was great finally getting to meet him after sending him so many (so very very many ) PMs. In the bar I sat down with Grumbuk a while and he told me all about the DX9 engine and the various problems that occurred with the collision engine.<br />
<br />
I also spoke with a dev who said that for the longest time expansions had been dictated down to them for every six months  and none of them really felt they could speak up and say heythis isint ready yet. He then said that the past month or so has seen some drastic changes and that he felt if he needed to he could walk into Smedleys office anytime with a problem. This struck me particularly because I was so used to working as intended, SoE is infallible that it was very refreshing to hear someone say that things hadnt been working and they were taking steps to fix it as opposed to just denying it.<br />
<br />
The following morning we headed to SoE headquarters and were greeted by the design team and John Smedley. Smedley talked to us a bit, calling GoD the worst mistake they had made in 5-years. Pertaining to Afterlife and other guilds leaving he said that it really upset him that they had let the game get so bad as to force some of their most dedicated players to leave. He released a couple important facts:<br />
<br />
1)	The average EQ player is between levels 30-50<br />
2)	GoD was originally designed to be Level 70<br />
3)	EQ and EQ2 teams receive separate royalties from their game (in other words, EQ staff get money for people playing EQ and EQ2 get money for people playing EQ2 so theyre competition with each other  e.g. The EQ guys will work hard to keep EQ going because if players cancel EQ1 accounts and move to EQ2 they lose their bonuses)<br />
<br />
Then the VP in charge of all the expansions (forget his name) stood up and apologized and basically said GoD was my fault. Hate me. It will never happen again. EQ will continue upgrading engine and PC models and Smedley stated he saw EQ lasting at least another 5 years through expansions. <br />
<br />
Then we got our tour of the SoE facilities. We got to tour the GM room and watch them answering some petitions. We also heard some great GM stories such as when a guild had been camping Ragefire all day and 2 GMs popped dragons in the zone named Rage and Fire. We toured the Quality Assurance area where there was a bulls-eye on the wall and a sign saying Bash head here. <br />
<br />
We saw the server room  I was a little disappointed there. Id been hoping to meet Guss the wonder hamster who powers the 386 running Fennin Ro  but alas he was nowhere to be seen. We also saw the server status room where the guys who bring the servers back up when they go down are along with a huge screen of data for bandwidth on all the servers. Everquest runs on Windows NT but all other games including EQ2 run on Linux.<br />
<br />
Then we sat down for our first discussion group  broken out into groups of 10 or so. Our first session was hosted by Craig  the same associate producer from the ball game. We brought up lots of issues. Some of the recurring themes were all the guildleaders were burned out from the tedious nature of running a guild, all the guilds had seen lots of members leave and were forced to do back-flagging, the failure of GoD, Quality testing issues, terrible customer service, lack of communication with the players, and nothing to do during non-raid hours. <br />
<br />
Craig spent a lot of time on quality assurance  namely what can we do to make sure Omens isnt released full of bugs like GoD was. Almost everyone agreed that a major problem was betabuffs. Level 40 characters were moving to GoD, buffing up to a lvl 65 with full PoTime gear and testing encounters  which SoE then tuned to. For Omens it looks like encounters will be done by whole guilds at a time (with casual guilds testing casual encounters and uber guilds testing uber encounters). <br />
<br />
No one guild would do all the testing thus spoiling the expansion and there would be some sort of reward for testing  but not the tokens from previous betas which led to token farming rather than bug reporting.<br />
<br />
For other issues there were two ideas proposed for the back-flagging problem. One was a guild flag idea where once a guild beats an encounter they would obtain a flag and from then on any member of the guild while in it would be able to use the flag. The other was flagging events would drop charge-based flagging items (such as a 5-charge stone) that you could then use to flag people later on. <br />
<br />
About this time, Woody started addressing casual issues. His main complaint was when a casual player can only log in for 2 hours at a time they want to be able to do something with that time other than go LFG for 90 minutes and then be rejected by a group because youre not as well equipped as an uber person. <br />
<br />
There were many ideas (both from players and SoE) on this issue, the results of which were: Some sort of task based quest system with 1-2 hour long tasks handed out which you could do by yourself or with one or two other people which result in a meaningful amount of experience. They also are considering adding single-player LdoNs. <br />
<br />
On the subject of LdoNs, a couple more things came up. I suggested and am continuing to push for an uber-level difficulty which has double the points, drops 170/170ish loot off rares and is considerably harder (basically Ikkinz single group trials). They will also be adding some elemental/time quality gear to the ldon vendors allowing anyone casual players who do ldons to have access to some of the same level equipment as raiding players.<br />
<br />
Quite a non-uber issues came up like tradeskills, faction, how we all want Morden Rasp to be slowly tortured and suffer a painful deatheventually we broke for lunch but not before I handed in my letter to Craig to give to Smedley. (See attachment at end)<br />
<br />
At lunch, I finally got to meet Scott Hartsman (Gallenite). Scott has always been a huge supporter of Graffes and it was great finally getting to meet him. We set up an interview with him with EQ2 and he said hed try to get some more exclusive screenshots sent our way. (And yes, he still wears the bandana). I picked his brain on EQ2 stuff for a good fifteen minutes or so and Im more psyched than ever about seeing it unfold in the coming months. <br />
<br />
After lunch we headed back to group discussions  ours this time was hosted by lead GM Altazar. He explained how terrible the old petition system was set up with the average problem to resolution time in the 2-3 weeks vicinity. With the new petition system installed last month its down to a couple of days and the end goal is 1-3 hours. <br />
<br />
They also mentioned the new guild critical tool, which will allow the guildleader and a few designated officer/members the ability to submit a guild critical issue that requires immediate GM attention such as ninja looting, major bugs (1 mob in tier 3 being stuck under world so whole raid has to stop), contested spawns, etc. Their goal response time for these issues is 10-20 minutes. Here is a letter we were given regarding this tool (keep in mind this is NOT final):<br />
<br />
------------------------------------------<br />
Greetings Guild Leaders,<br />
 <br />
Thank you for attending the 2004 EQ Guild Summit.  Your input is very important to us.  As you may already know, we have recently implemented a new support tool (CS Assist), and our objective with this new tool is to respond to your inquiries fasters.  There are many situations where certain issues need immediate attention due to timing issues on a spawn or a disruption between groups.  To resolve these issues at faster pace, we are offering a separate support avenue for the Guild Leaders on every server.  This form of support will be used for Guild Critical issues, and every Guild Leader on every server will have the option to use this service.<br />
 <br />
Due to resource limitations, we ask that you read and understand the following policy and procedure before using this service.<br />
 <br />
Policy:<br />
The following issues may be submitted for a Guild Critical issue.<br />
1)      Spawn Disputes (When NPC triggers or Targets are spawned)<br />
2)      Raid Disruption (Training, Harassment, Kill Stealing, Leap Frogging, and Ninjalooting)<br />
3)      Character Flag Issues (NPC being under the world or not spawning).  This may only be used if this affects a significant portion of your guild.<br />
4)      Incorrect Event Functionality<br />
 <br />
Guild Leaders will be limited to submitting a request 3 times a week during In-Game business hours Monday through Sunday (designate a time).  We will be able to verify that the Guild Leaders are sending in the request based on their email address.  If you have a new email address, please update your registration information, and let us know.<br />
 <br />
Procedure:<br />
1)      The Guild Leader submits a request to [Email Removed by Gemdiver  not sure if they want this released yet ]<br />
2)      Provide the one of the following text on the subject line:  Guild Critical  Spawn Dispute,  Guild Critical  NPC Name spawned, Guild Critical  Raid Disruption, Guild Critical  Flagging Issue, or Guild Critical  Event Dysfunction<br />
3)      Provide the Guild Leader, Guild, and Server name.<br />
4)      Please be as detailed as possible in your message by providing all parties involved including character names, NPC names, zone<br />
 <br />
The response time on your issues will depend on the volume of requests, however we will be making every effort to answer these requests within a 15 to 30 minutes period.<br />
 <br />
We may discuss any loop-holes during the CS panel discussion to make this work out better for you.  Please feel free to express your opinions.  The Guild Critical issue process will evolve as we determine better ways to address this and implement improvements to our new CS Assist program.<br />
 <br />
 <br />
Sincerely,<br />
 <br />
Customer Service Department<br />
Sony Online Entertainment<br />
---------------------------------------------------<br />
<br />
They are also changing the roles of GMs and guides. One of the major complaints about guides was that you would sit in a petition queue for hours and eventually a guide would respond and say they were very sorry but there was nothing they could do  and bump you up to the GM line. <br />
<br />
With the new petition system, GMs and Guides can see what sort of issue it is. If its an issue a guide can handle (name change, policy question, etc) they can handle it, and if its an issue a GM needs to handle (plooting, harassment, etc) the GM can come to it. This assures that the person who responds to your petition will be someone who is able to resolve it. <br />
<br />
Guides will now spend the majority of their time running events to enrich the playing experience. SoE is working on creating pre-packaged events complete with mobs and NPCs that have storylines and everything planned out. A guide will be able to go into a zone and trigger the event and everything else will run automatically. In my opinion this will add a lot towards the immersion aspect. As a note in the near future well be doing an interview with Lead GM Altazar who will give us some more info in regards to GMs, Guides, and Customer Service issues.<br />
<br />
We then took a short break before the developer meeting. In this time I got to see some EQ2 stuff and talked with John Blakely, the senior producer for Everquest II along with one of the people contributing to the project. (John also agreed to do an interview with us sometime in the future). Got to see some really neat stuff that I think everyone is going to absolutely love. <br />
<br />
The developer meeting was really what everyone had been waiting for. The Youre in our world now slogan was replaced with Microsofts Where do you want to go today? as we tossed all manner of suggestions to them regarding the game. Im just going to do this in a list format since there were so many.<br />
<br />
<br />
·	54 person raids (no more raising and lowering the limit)<br />
·	Epic Weapons 2.0  These will be very in depth and have many phases to complete them, some raiding, some quest, some trade skill (though you can get someone else with the skill to do the part for you). It will have different phases so that more casual players can get a meaningful item too. One of the suggestions for the wizard epic was to have it have 4 shards (Staff of the four) and each one you get you combine with the others to complete a full staff but also have a decent item if you only have 2 or 3.<br />
·	Solutions to back-flagging<br />
·	Taking the tedious things out of raiding  being able to loot your whole corpse, dragging multiple corpses at once, etc. Also be able to have a main assist or raid leader filter for text to have them a different color. Also expand expedition window to see people who are in your expedition but logged off or are afk in other zones.<br />
·	Casual content  this included tasks quests, solo LdoNs, ways to encourage grouping, GM events, ways to gain experience when only being able to logon for short periods at a time.<br />
·	Augmentations and charms  suggested being able to remove augments from an item with solvent rather than destroy.<br />
·	Raise some of the limits  buff slots, FT, etc. (they said they werent opposed to raiding the FT cap in Omens and would consider it)<br />
<br />
That ended the official summit. So now Ill go into some other things that I did at various points around the bar or through PMs when I got back and such. A private message board has been set up for all of us, as of 2 pm Tuesday it already has over 60 posts on it. <br />
<br />
All the devs have introduced themselves along with what they cover and every time someone has posted a question or issue a developer or producer from SoE has responded very quickly  this is very encouraging and suggests that open communication between SoE and the players will continue even though the summit is over. Here is the letter we received at dinner after the summitplease note this list is FAR from complete and weve been told well get an in depth and prioritized list in a couple days which Ill post here<br />
<br />
June 5, 2004 <br />
<br />
Dear Guild and Community Representatives, <br />
<br />
Thank you very much for a great Summit! By all accounts it was a huge success. I can speak for the EverQuest Development Team and tell you that we're grateful for the input you provided. In fact, in trying to generate this list to give to you this evening, we realized there was so much to go over that wouldn't be able to get a complete list together in time. We're committed to not only listening to your feedback, but working with you to make EverQuest more enjoyable for years to come. <br />
<br />
So, we decided to list the Top Ten themes we would address starting Monday, as well as the most common themes that we'll come back with more information n by mid-week next week. <br />
<br />
A quick discussion resulted in a list of items that we will immediately address: <br />
<br />
- Add scripting to shut off empty instances of Plane of Time <br />
- Raid messages of the day <br />
- Improving how we handle beta and the testing process <br />
- Increase the number of debuffs allowed on the MOBs <br />
<br />
- Increase buffs on players through AAs <br />
- Note field on raid window <br />
- Improved consent &amp; drag for raid, group and guild <br />
- Improve corpse drag radius <br />
<br />
- Make charms not no-drop <br />
- Guild and individual rewards for guild beta testing <br />
- Work on large To Do list....I know this one is a little random <br />
<br />
Future items we will immediately begin looking at and discussions are as follows: <br />
<br />
- Plane of Time instancing and other issues <br />
- Back flaggings solutions to help with High-end guild atrophy <br />
- Improved raid and guild functionality <br />
- Auto loot all for your corpse <br />
- Improvements to Raid XP <br />
<br />
- Review the Epic 2.0 quests <br />
- No more alien NPCs (focusing more on familiar Norrathians themes) <br />
- Solo LDoN-stype instances or similar content <br />
- Issues with item augmentations <br />
- Possible enhancements to Guild Wars <br />
<br />
Of course these aren't all of the items. You brought us a CD, 2 books, 20 printed sheets and a manifesto. We'll need to go through all of those and our notes before we can really get a good tally of all of the wonderful ideas and questions that were presented. <br />
<br />
Thank you again for your feedback and participation. We've had a great weekend and a wonderful display of things to come. <br />
<br />
Sincerely, <br />
<br />
Robert Pfister <br />
Executive Producer <br />
EverQuest<br />
<br />
<br />
Im currently talking to Rashere regarding wizard AA for Omens (hell be doing some Q &amp; A on our forums), Rytan has also agreed to do an interview with Graffes updating us on the status of the issues we submitted a while ago, and we have an interview coming at the end of the week or early next week with Alan Crosby (Brenlo) regarding how best to explain the guild summits bar tab to SmedleyI mean the current state of the wizard class. <br />
<br />
So now let me summarize and conclude and talk about what was accomplished<br />
<br />
We have interviewsso many interviews:<br />
<br />
Brenlo  EQ Community manager - Current state of wizard class<br />
John Blakely  EQ2 Senior Producer  EQ2 General Interview<br />
Scott Hartsman (Gallenite)  EQ2 Tech Director: EQ2 General Interview <br />
Rashere (Travis)  Regarding OoW AAs <br />
Rytan  Update on the class issues we submitted<br />
Altazar  Lead GM  Update on customer service issues<br />
<br />
As you can seethe channels of communication are most definitely open and they are hearing us and willing to listen to us. It is my goal to bring at least 2 interviews per month from different staff members to keep us updated on whats going on at SoE. Im going to try and get John Smedley to make an appearance but I havent asked yet so no promises there.<br />
<br />
It seems to me that if there was any one thing that was accomplished from this event it was opening the channels. With the new forum and SoEs willingness to come visit fan sites again it is ensuring they will hear how players feel and be able to respond accordingly. <br />
<br />
Already since Ive gotten back Ive started discussing Omens spells/AA, the GoD robe (or lack thereof) new ldon adventures, and all sorts of ideas directly with the people who can make it happen. <br />
<br />
This is an exciting time for Everquest. Ive been a strong supporter of them a while but I honestly had my doubts  When I first saw the invitation I was thinking ok so where does it say To RSVP just send your login and password to the following address. I was blown away though by their candid response and willingness to change the game to make it better. Right when John Smedley called GoD the biggest cluster of EQ, we all knew it was for real. <br />
<br />
I encourage anyone  casual or uber, gnome or erudite, tunarian or solusek  who has an issue with EQ or suggestion to start posting it in the class balance forum. I will periodically read it and relay information to the developers (who can then respond through the Q&amp;A and interviews we will now be doing on a regular basis) <br />
<br />
This event marks a turning point in Everquest from the downward spiraling level of enjoyment and general apathy of SoE towards its players to a return of a game thats fun to play for everyone regardless of casual or uber with open communication flowing both ways between Sony and the players.<br />
<br />
For all those people who doubted the sincerity of SoEs invitation or their dedication to bringing the game back to its former glory  the past 48 hours since the summit ended have already seen a plethora of changes beginning to take place on test with more being announced every hour. Within the next couple months it will become apparent to everyone, that Everquest is entering a new phase that will be challenging, exciting, and fun to everyone in the land. <br />
<br />
While lots of people both at SoE and from the community contributed a lot this weekend, Id like to point out a couple people who we all should thank for their input in the event (in no particular order)<br />
<br />
Brenlo/Vannoth (Alan and Tom)  These guys set the whole thing up. They sit around telling jokes and war stories and drink beer with the players. Thanks for making a kick ass weekend and I look forward to fan faire and the next summit. You guys own.<br />
<br />
John Smedley  For making this important decision to open up SoE to the players and truly make the game the enjoyable experience it used to be (and for footing the air fare, hotel bill, and bar tab =D )<br />
<br />
Gallenite (Scott Hartsman)  Was great finally meeting him, he had a wealth of information about EQ2 not to mention one of the coolest and nicest guys at SoE. Im really looking forward to doing the interview with him.<br />
<br />
Craig Knapp  The associate producer who I spoke at length with. I hope we can keep in touch regarding omens and some of the other topics we discussed.<br />
<br />
Baelish (Greg Short)  Im glad we finally got to meet and talk. Like Scott, you also had a great wealth of info you were willing to share with me. As soon as I manage to dig up your email address Ive got some ideas for you. <br />
<br />
Chenier (Druids Grove), Frika (Safehouse), and Juwel (The Runes)  Was really nice meeting some of my colleagues from other class sites. You guys are welcome any time on Graffes. <br />
<br />
Ashlanne, Kytherea, and all the SoE staff: Thanks for making a fantastic weekend! <br />
<br />
And of course<br />
<br />
Graffes Community  for giving me the opportunity to represent our community.<br />
<br />
And just in case you all think that Im exaggerating how great this whole summit has been and how it will change Everquest for the better, here are some other summaries by the people who went:<br />
<br />
Druids Grove: <a href="http://thedruidsgrove.org/forums/showthread.php?t=8094" target="_blank">http://thedruidsgrove.org/forums/showthread.php?t=8094</a><br />
Steel Warriors: <a href="http://www.thesteelwarrior.org/forum/showthread.php?t=7457" target="_blank">http://www.thesteelwarrior.org/forum...ead.php?t=7457</a><br />
The Runes: <a href="http://www.therunes.net/forums/viewtopic.php?t=4178" target="_blank">http://www.therunes.net/forums/viewtopic.php?t=4178</a><br />
Safehouse: <a href="http://www.thesafehouse.org/viewtopic.php?p=145875" target="_blank">http://www.thesafehouse.org/viewtopic.php?p=145875</a><br />
GU Comics (Woody): <a href="http://forums.gucomics.com/viewtopic.php?t=2220" target="_blank">http://forums.gucomics.com/viewtopic.php?t=2220</a><br />
Mobhunter: <a href="http://www.mobhunter.com/article.jsp?articleid=-1863105531" target="_blank">http://www.mobhunter.com/article.jsp...id=-1863105531</a><br />
Casters Realm: <a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=5406" target="_blank">http://eq.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=5406</a><br />
Paladins of Norrath: <a href="http://p202.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showMessage?topicID=19890.topic" target="_blank">http://p202.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofn...=1989  0.topic</a><br />
Talisman (pictures!): <a href="http://www.talismanguild.org/" target="_blank">http://www.talismanguild.org/</a><br />
<br />
Ill post some pictures sometime later on tonight. All in all, it was a fantastic event. I encourage everyone to actively make suggestions to make the game better. It is what we make of it, and I for one want to make it the best it can possibly be.<br />
<br />
From now on, whenever we log in to EverQuest we truly will be in OUR world now. <br />
<br />
-Gemdiver Myrcide</div>
